                       =20
<p><strong>Learn how to create a bootable Windows 10 USB on Ubuntu or Linux=
 Mint using a free application called =E2=80=98WoeUSB=E2=80=99, all detaile=
d in this guide.</strong></p>



<p>While I don=E2=80=99t use Windows 10 as my main OS I sometimes need to u=
se it to try things out for this site. When I need to create a bootable Win=
dows 10 USB to install from, I like doing it from my main OS, which is Ubun=
tu.</p>



<p>There are a few ways to perform this particular task, but the steps in t=
his use what I consider to be the <strong>easy way to create a bootable Win=
dows 10 USB</strong> (plus one that actually boots).</p>



<p>Ready to learn more?</p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading">How to Create Bootable Windows 10 USB on Ubu=
ntu</h2>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter"><a href=3D"https://149366088.v2.pressablecdn.=
com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/windows-10-ubuntu.jpg"><img fetchpriority=3D=
"high" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"750" height=3D"414" src=3D"https://14936=
6088.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/windows-10-ubuntu-750x4=
14.jpg" alt=3D"create windows 10 usb on Ubuntu linux" class=3D"wp-image-121=
965"></a><figcaption class=3D"wp-element-caption">Windows 10</figcaption></=
figure></div>


<p><a href=3D"https://github.com/slacka/WoeUSB" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"no=
opener noreferrer">WoeUSB</a> is the (oddly named) app to use to make a boo=
table Windows 10 USB stick on Ubuntu. A fork of an earlier tool called WinU=
SB, WoeUSB is free, open-source software that=E2=80=99s available as a grap=
hical app (GUI) or a command-line (CLI) client.</p>



<p>In this tutorial I use WoeUSB GUI app.</p>


<a data-vars-plausible=3D"{&quot;category&quot;:&quot;Promoted Story&quot;,=
&quot;props&quot;:{&quot;from&quot;:&quot;\/2017\/06\/create-bootable-windo=
ws-10-usb-ubuntu&quot;,&quot;to&quot;:&quot;\/how-to-install-wsl2-on-window=
s-10&quot;,&quot;key&quot;:&quot;\/how-to-install-wsl2-on-windows-10 (from:=
 \/2017\/06\/create-bootable-windows-10-usb-ubuntu)&quot;}}" class=3D"omg-p=
romoted-story alignright has-image" href=3D"https://www.omgubuntu.co.uk/how=
-to-install-wsl2-on-windows-10" target=3D"_blank">
    <div class=3D"omg-promoted-story__image-container">
    <img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://149366088.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp=
-content/uploads/2020/04/ubuntu-20.4-wsl.jpg">
  </div> =20
  <div class=3D"omg-promoted-story__content">
    <span class=3D"omg-promoted-story__caption">Related Guide</span>
    <div class=3D"omg-promoted-story__text">How to Install WSL 2 on Windows=
 10</div>
  </div>
</a>


<p>Using WoeUSB you can make a bootable USB for a number of Windows release=
s, including Windows Vista, Windows 7, Window 8, and Windows 10.&nbsp;</p>



<p>All languages and all variants of Windows, including Pro, Home, N, 32-bi=
t, and more, are supported, and the tool works with both =E2=80=98legacy=E2=
=80=99 and =E2=80=98UEFI=E2=80=99 boot-modes.</p>



<p>For advanced needs you may prefer to use the WoeUSB CLI as it offers an =
array of flags, arguments, and switches to curate a custom install for spec=
ialist needs. </p>



<p>But for most of us, the GUI WoeUSB app is all that=E2=80=99s needed.</p>



<p>Before you begin make sure you have all of the following things handy, a=
s all are required to create a bootable Windows 10 USB on Ubuntu:</p>



<ul>
<li><strong>WoeUSB app</strong></li>



<li><strong>USB flash drive (4GB minimum)</strong></li>



<li><strong>Windows 10 ISO file</strong></li>
</ul>



<p>You can <a href=3D"https://www.microsoft.com/en-gb/software-download/win=
dows10" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">download Windows 10 d=
isc images</a> from the Microsoft website, so if you don=E2=80=99t have one=
 you can go there to get one. You will need a valid Windows license to acti=
vate and use Windows, but you don=E2=80=99t need one to create an installab=
le USB of Windows, or actually perform the install.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">1. Install WoeUSB on Ubuntu</h3>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-large"><a href=3D"https://149366088.v2.pr=
essablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/woeusb.jpg"><img decoding=3D"asyn=
c" width=3D"750" height=3D"410" src=3D"https://149366088.v2.pressablecdn.co=
m/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/woeusb-750x410.jpg" alt=3D"WoeUSB launcher" cl=
ass=3D"wp-image-224285"></a><figcaption class=3D"wp-element-caption">Gettin=
g the WoeUSB app</figcaption></figure></div>


<p>First the drawback: WoeUSB is no longer actively maintained upstream, me=
aning you can=E2=80=99t download the tool direct from its original GitHub p=
age. </p>



<p>However, since the tool is so frickin=E2=80=99 useful the community has =
stepped in to <a href=3D"https://github.com/WoeUSB/WoeUSB" target=3D"_blank=
" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">fork the app</a> and continue development. A =
<a href=3D"https://launchpad.net/~tomtomtom/+archive/ubuntu/woeusb" target=
=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">personal package archive</a> (PPA) =
makes it easy to <strong>install WoebUSB on Ubuntu </strong>18.04, 20.04, a=
nd 22.04 LTS versions (only).</p>



<p>Add the WoeUSB PPA to your list of software sources by running the follo=
wing two commands from the terminal app:</p>



<pre id=3D"yui_3_10_3_1_1602799644335_70" class=3D"wp-block-preformatted">s=
udo add-apt-repository ppa:tomtomtom/woeusb</pre>



<pre class=3D"wp-block-preformatted">sudo apt update &amp;&amp; sudo apt in=
stall woeusb-frontend-wxgtk</pre>



<p>If you use a 32-bit version of Ubuntu 16.04 LTS you will need to downloa=
d an older<a href=3D"http://ppa.launchpad.net/nilarimogard/webupd8/ubuntu/p=
ool/main/w/woeusb/woeusb_3.3.1-1~webupd8~xenial0_i386.deb" target=3D"_blank=
" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer"> 32-bit WoeUSB installer</a>, and then instal=
l it. </p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">2. Run WoeUSB</h3>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-large"><a href=3D"https://149366088.v2.pr=
essablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/woeusb-windows-usb-installer.jpg"=
><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"750" height=3D"410" src=
=3D"https://149366088.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/woeusb=
-windows-usb-installer-750x410.jpg" alt=3D"The WoeUSB tool running on the U=
buntu desktop" class=3D"wp-image-224280"></a><figcaption class=3D"wp-elemen=
t-caption">The WoeUSB GUI</figcaption></figure></div>


<p>Once the WoeUSB app is installed on your system, open it. You=E2=80=99ll=
 find a shortcut for it in the application menu/grid, or on Ubuntu Ubuntu y=
ou can press the <code>Super</code> key and type =E2=80=98WoeUSB=E2=80=99 t=
o find it.</p>



<p>The app is quick to open and is easy to use.</p>



<p>First, select a valid Windows 10 .ISO image using the file selector butt=
on, then select the USB drive you want to write it to from the =E2=80=98Tar=
get device=E2=80=99 section.</p>



<p>If you don=E2=80=99t see a USB device listed in the =E2=80=98Target devi=
ce=E2=80=99 section do make sure it=E2=80=99s plugged in correctly, and the=
n click the =E2=80=98refresh=E2=80=99 button to update the list of attached=
 devices.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">3. Create Windows 10 Bootable USB</h3>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-large"><a href=3D"https://149366088.v2.pr=
essablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/creating.jpg"><img loading=3D"laz=
y" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"750" height=3D"410" src=3D"https://149366088=
.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/creating-750x410.jpg" alt=
=3D"WoeUSB on the Ubuntu desktop writing a Windows ISO to a USB" class=3D"w=
p-image-224281"></a><figcaption class=3D"wp-element-caption">Installing=E2=
=80=A6</figcaption></figure></div>


<p>Before you hit =E2=80=98install=E2=80=99 to create your bootable Windows=
 USB <strong><em>please</em></strong> double-check yo have selected the cor=
rect drive first. The install process will totally wipe/erase the contents =
of the selected USB drive, and you will lose any data stored on it.</p>



<p>Other than that, the tool does the rest. Let it run its course</p>



<p>Once the image write is complete a small notification appears. Close Woe=
USB, eject the USB drive you made, then use plug it in to a laptop or PC an=
d boot from it to install Windows 10.</p>



<p><strong>Let me know how you get on down in the comments!</strong></p>
